# tess auditd rules — tamper-EVIDENCE / forensic audit only, NOT a security boundary.
#
# These watches record write and attribute changes to the installed tess binaries, PAM module,
# PAM helper, the TPM-access udev rule, and the system session stack. They exist so that AFTER a
# compromise an operator (or a remote log collector) has forensic evidence that a tess-relevant
# file was modified.
#
# This is explicitly NOT a security control:
#   - A root/kernel attacker on a live machine is out of scope for tess by design. Such an attacker
#     can disable auditd, flush its rules (`auditctl -D`), unload the kernel audit subsystem, or
#     edit/forge the logs — these watches stop none of that.
#   - The protection tess provides is at-rest (a stolen/powered-off disk) plus TPM hardware
#     anti-hammering. auditd adds after-the-fact evidence on a running system, nothing more.
#   - Do not treat the presence of these rules as preventing tampering. They only make undetected
#     tampering harder, on the assumption logs are shipped off-box to a collector the attacker does
#     not control.
#
# NOT auto-activated. The .deb ships this file to /usr/share/tess/auditd/tess.rules; an admin opts
# in by copying it into the auditd rules directory and reloading:
#
#     sudo cp /usr/share/tess/auditd/tess.rules /etc/audit/rules.d/tess.rules
#     sudo augenrules --load        # or: sudo systemctl restart auditd
#
# Review with:   ausearch -k tess-binary    (and the other -k keys below)
# Remove with:   sudo rm /etc/audit/rules.d/tess.rules && sudo augenrules --load
#
# The per-user sealed metadata/recovery blobs under ~/.local/share/tess are intentionally NOT
# watched here: they are per-user paths a system-wide auditd ruleset cannot enumerate, and they are
# already inert without the TPM and PIN (sealed blob) or the offline recovery secret (recovery blob).
#
# auditctl(8) / audit.rules(7): -w <path> -p <perms> -k <key>; `wa` = write + attribute change.

-w /usr/bin/tess -p wa -k tess-binary
-w /usr/lib/tess/tess-pam-helper -p wa -k tess-binary
-w /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/security/pam_tess.so -p wa -k tess-pam
-w /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/70-tess-tpm.rules -p wa -k tess-udev
-w /etc/pam.d/common-session -p wa -k tess-pam-stack
